uary 17, 2020|accessdate=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|E of [[New Site, Mississippi|New Site]]\n|[[Prentiss County, Mississippi|Prentiss]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|34.5566|-88.4382|name=New Site (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|22:14\u201322:15\n|{{convert|0.5|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|75|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|The roof of a barn was ripped off, and a carport and sheds were damaged.\n|<ref name=\"1216MEG\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Memphis, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey for New Site Mississippi Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMEG&e=201912172208|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|[[Tishomingo, Mississippi|Tishomingo]]\n|[[Tishomingo County, Mississippi|Tishomingo]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|34.6240|-88.2287|name=Tishomingo (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|22:27\u201322:31\n|{{convert|4|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|150|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Approximately 15 homes and 1 business suffered damage. Trees were damaged as well.\n|<ref name=\"1216MEG\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|[[Columbia, Mississippi|Columbia]]\n|[[Marion County, Mississippi|Marion]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|31.1927|-89.9206|name=Columbia (Dec. 16, EF2)}}\n|22:41\u201322:52\n|{{convert|7.49|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A strong, multiple-vortex tornado partially ripped the roof off a collision center, damaged its exterior walls, and shattered its windows. A car was tossed over the storefront, and other nearby vehicles were moved or flipped. A library in Columbia suffered roof damage, and power poles were snapped. Numerous trees were snapped or uprooted as well. Three people were injured.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|NE of [[Silver Creek, Mississippi|Silver Creek]]\n|[[Lawrence County, Mississippi|Lawrence]], [[Jefferson Davis County, Mississippi|Jefferson Davis]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|31.6159|-90.0076|name=Silver Creek (Dec. 16, EF2)}}\n|22:44\u201323:00\n|{{convert|10.92|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|600|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Two homes were destroyed while a third had most of its roof removed as a result of this high-end EF2 tornado. A cinder block store was destroyed, and a group of three chicken houses were damaged. A mobile home was destroyed, and one person was injured after being thrown out of the structure. A nearby truck was tossed about {{convert|30|yd|m|abbr=on}}. Numerous trees were snapped or uprooted, and multiple power poles were broken.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|ESE of [[Cherokee, Alabama|Cherokee]]\n|[[Colbert County, Alabama|Colbert]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.7043|-87.8715|name=Cherokee (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|22:50\u201322:52\n|{{convert|0.68|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|75|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Some tree trunks were snapped.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Huntsville, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/16/2019 Tornado Event - Update #6|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=201912211847|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|[[Colbert Heights, Alabama|Colbert Heights]]\n|[[Colbert County, Alabama|Colbert]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.64|-87.7331|name=Colbert Heights (Dec. 16, EF2)}}\n|22:52\u201323:01\n|{{convert|8.18|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|250|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Numerous trees were snapped or uprooted throughout Colbert Heights. Several sheds were heavily damaged. One home had its roof entirely removed, with bricks blown off its west-facing wall and windows shattered as well. Three other homes suffered extensive roof damage, and others still sustained at least minor damage. A camping trailer was overturned.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|W of [[Lawrenceburg, Tennessee|Lawrenceburg]]\n|[[Lawrence County, Tennessee|Lawrence]]\n|[[Tennessee|TN]]\n|{{Coord|35.269|-87.519|name=Lawrenceburg (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|22:55\u201322:59\n|{{convert|3.76|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|25|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|The front porch and a portion of the roof was ripped off one house, and its toilet was uplifted about {{convert|1|ft|m|abbr=on}} above the flooring. A second house had a large number of its shingles removed. A large farm outbuilding was collapsed and another outbuilding saw its roof damaged. Sporadic tree damage was observed.\n|<ref name=\"1216OHX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Nashville, Tennessee|title=NWS Damage Survey for December 16, 2019 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSOHX&e=202001092052|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=January 10, 2020|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|NE of [[Columbia, Mississippi|Columbia]]\n|[[Marion County, Mississippi|Marion]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|31.2824|-89.7682|name=Columbia (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|22:56\u201323:07\n|{{convert|6.21|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|440|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Trees were snapped and uprooted. A couple of sheds were collapsed and some shingles from ripped from a home as well.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|S of [[Town Creek, Alabama|Town Creek]]\n|[[Lawrence County, Alabama|Lawrence]], [[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.6445|-87.4126|name=Town Creek (Dec. 16, EF2)}}\n|23:08\u201323:31\n|{{convert|18.58|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|370|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|2 deaths \u2013 A strong tornado significantly damaged several mobile homes. One double-wide mobile home was rolled off its plot and destroyed, resulting in two fatalities. Three injuries occurred among the damaged structures. Near the end of the tornado's path, a small mobile home was shifted slightly off its plot while a small and well-built block outbuilding was largely demolished. Trees were damaged along the entirety of the track.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat3}} | EF3\n|[[Sumrall, Mississippi|Southern Sumrall]]\n|[[Lamar County, Mississippi|Lamar]], [[Covington County, Mississippi|Covington]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|31.3902|-89.5764|name=Sumrall (Dec. 16, EF3)}}\n|23:17\u201323:25\n|{{convert|5.84|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|560|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|An intense multiple-vortex tornado impacted the south edge of Sumrall and ripped the roof off a well-built brick group home, and collapsed one of its exterior walls. Six vehicles were tossed {{convert|40|\u2013|60|yd|m|abbr=on}} from the parking lot into a pile, and large trees were ripped out of the ground. An insulation company sustained damage to its metal storage building, where some walls were blown out. A sports complex sustained damage to its fence and bleachers. Numerous trees were snapped or uprooted, and a few homes were damaged as well. Seven people were injured.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat3}} | EF3\n|NNW of [[Mount Olive, Mississippi|Mount Olive]] to [[Mize, Mississippi|Mize]] to SW of [[Sylvarena, Mississippi|Sylvarena]]\n|[[Simpson County, Mississippi|Simpson]], [[Smith County, Mississippi|Smith]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]]\n|{{Coord|31.7925|-89.6781|name=Mount Olive (Dec. 16, EF3)}}\n|23:19\u201323:51\n|{{convert|18.75|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|1320|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A tornado began near the small community of [[Saratoga, Mississippi|Saratoga]] and moved to the northeast, damaging a church in addition to a few other buildings, sheds, and homes. Three different groups of chicken houses were heavily damaged or destroyed as the tornado continued northeastward. Southwest of Mize, a well-built house had its roof ripped off and a majority of its exterior walls collapsed. Two trucks were thrown {{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on}} into a pasture, and a few ATVs were thrown considerable distances as well. Multiple structures and chicken houses were damaged to the north of town, and another well-built house lost its roof and one of its outer walls. A large shed was destroyed and a tractor and boat were tossed {{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on}}. Along the entirety of the path, trees and power lines were downed.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|[[Joe Wheeler State Park]]\n|[[Lauderdale County, Alabama|Lauderdale]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.8017|-87.3322|name=Joe Wheeler State Park (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|23:20\u201323:24\n|{{convert|2.9|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|500|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Thousands of trees were either snapped or uprooted by a multiple-vortex tornado.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|E of [[Athens, Alabama|Athens]]\n|[[Limestone County, Alabama|Limestone]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.6997|-87.1010|name=Athens (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|23:30\u201323:43\n|{{convert|9.47|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Tree trunks were snapped, and a home had most of its roof ripped off.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|E of [[Cornersville, Tennessee|Cornersville]]\n|[[Marshall County, Tennessee|Marshall]]\n|[[Tennessee|TN]]\n|{{Coord|35.361|-86.823|name=Cornersville (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|23:41\u201323:45\n|{{convert|3.45|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|An outbuilding was collapsed, numerous shingles were ripped from a house, the metal roofing and siding was removed from a metal carport, and trees were sporadically uprooted.\n|<ref name=\"1216OHX\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|NE of [[Ardmore, Tennessee|Ardmore]]\n|[[Lincoln County, Tennessee|Lincoln]]\n|[[Tennessee|TN]]\n|{{Coord|35.0106|-86.8261|name=Ardmore (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|23:50\u201323:52\n|{{convert|3.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several trees were uprooted, and a house sustained minor damage.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Huntsville, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/16/2019 Tornado Event - Update #7|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSHUN&e=202001211630|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=January 21, 2020|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|[[Monrovia, Alabama|Monrovia]]\n|[[Madison County, Alabama|Madison]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.7904|-86.7366|name=Monrovia (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|23:54\u201300:00\n|{{convert|1.25|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|25|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|One home had two thirds of its roof ripped off, while homes in town sustained lesser damage, at least partially the result of flying debris such as an awning, along with fence segments and posts. A small outdoor metal shed was damaged, and numerous trees were snapped or uprooted.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat3}} | EF3\n|[[Laurel, Mississippi|Laurel]] to WNW of [[Lisman, Alabama|Lisman, AL]]\n|[[Jones County, Mississippi|Jones]], [[Wayne County, Mississippi|Wayne]], [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke]], [[Choctaw County, Alabama|Choctaw (AL)]]\n|[[Mississippi|MS]], [[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|31.6724|-89.1726|name=Laurel (Dec. 16, EF3)}}\n|23:59\u201301:29\n|{{convert|61.31|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|[[Tornado outbreak of December 16\u201317, 2019#Laurel \u2013 Sandersville \u2013 Shubuta \u2013 Mannassa, Mississippi/Lisman, Alabama|See section on this tornado]] \u2013 Two people were injuried.\n|<ref name=\"1216JAN\" /><ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Mobile, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/16/2019 Choctaw County Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSMOB&e=201912180115|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|SW of [[Meridianville, Alabama|Meridianville]]\n|[[Madison County, Alabama|Madison]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|34.8593|-86.6252|name=Meridianville (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|00:05\u201300:12\n|{{convert|3.16|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|37|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Numerous trees were downed, and a couple of homes suffered minor roof damage.\n|<ref name=\"1216HUN\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|W of [[Demopolis, Alabama|Demopolis]]\n|[[Marengo County, Alabama|Marengo]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|32.4206|-87.9787|name=Demopolis (Dec. 16, EF2)}}\n|02:07\u201302:16\n|{{convert|5.95|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several homes suffered roof and structural damage, including one that had its roof completely removed and sustained partial wall collapse. Two mobile homes were completely demolished nearby, resulting in three injuries. Extensive tree damage was observed.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Birmingham, Alabama|title=NWS Damage Survey for December 16th Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSBMX&e=201912180140|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|NW of [[Morgan Springs, Alabama|Morgan Springs]]\n|[[Hale County, Alabama|Hale]], [[Perry County, Alabama|Perry]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|32.7695|-87.4927|name=Morgan Springs (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|03:03\u201303:12\n|{{convert|5.38|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|300|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|At least 100 trees were snapped or uprooted.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|NE of [[Gary Springs, Alabama|Gary Springs]]\n|[[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|32.9800|-87.0507|name=Gary Springs (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|03:49\u201303:55\n|{{convert|3.12|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A few trees and limbs were downed.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|N of [[Brierfield, Alabama|Brierfield]]\n|[[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|33.0416|-86.9401|name=Brierfield (Dec. 16, EF1)}}\n|04:00\u201304:04\n|{{convert|2.6|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|300|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Dozens of trees were snapped or uprooted, and a barn was damaged as well.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|E of [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]]\n|[[Shelby County, Alabama|Shelby]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|33.0851|-86.8429|name=Montevallo (Dec. 16, EF0)}}\n|04:07\u201304:12\n|{{convert|2.29|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|An outbuilding was destroyed, two mobile homes suffered minor damage, and dozens of trees were snapped or uprooted. A house sustained minor roof damage, and a deputy sheriff was blown off the road in his vehicle.\n|<ref name=\"1216BMX\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n===December 17 event===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|+ List of confirmed tornadoes \u2013 Tuesday, December 17, 2019{{efn|All dates are based on the local [[time zone]] where the tornado touched down; however, all times are in [[Coordinated Universal Time]] for consistency.|group=note|name=Date/Time}}\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|[[Enhanced Fujita scale|EF#]]\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:7%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\"|County / parish\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:5%; text-align:center;\"|State\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Start coord.\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Time ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Path length\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:6%; text-align:center;\"|Max width\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:48%; text-align:center;\"|Summary\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:3%; text-align:center;\"|Refs\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|N of [[Rock Hill, Georgia|Rock Hill]]\n|[[Early County, Georgia|Early]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.355|-85.0228|name=Rock Hill (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|12:30\u201312:33\n|{{convert|0.39|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|50|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|A few trees were snapped and blown in opposing directions.\n|<ref name=\"1217TAE\">{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/17/19 Tornado Event - Update 2|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912180058|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 17, 2019|accessdate=December 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|[[Madrid, Alabama|Madrid]]\n|[[Houston County, Alabama|Houston]]\n|[[Alabama|AL]]\n|{{Coord|31.03|-85.39|name=Madrid (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|12:52\n|<!--{{convert|6.57|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}-->unknown\n|<!--{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}-->unknown\n|One home lost a garage and outbuilding. A few dozen softwood trees were uprooted or snapped.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=Preliminary Local Storm Report|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=LSRTAE&e=201912201913|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat1}} | EF1\n|E of [[Jeterville, Georgia|Jeterville]]\n|[[Miller County, Georgia|Miller]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.2046|-84.7031|name=Jeterville (Dec. 17, EF1)}}\n|14:27\u201314:36\n|{{convert|6.57|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|200|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Barns, trees, and farm equipment was damaged.\n|<ref name=\"1217TAE\" />\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|storm}} | EF0\n|WSW of [[Newton, Georgia|Newton]]\n|[[Baker County, Georgia|Baker]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.3074|-84.3932|name=Newton (Dec. 17, EF0)}}\n|15:00\u201315:02\n|{{convert|0.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|75|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Several trees were snapped, a mobile home was slid off its support about {{convert|3|ft|m|abbr=on}} and had its roof damaged, and an irrigation pivot was damaged.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=Brief EF-0 Tornado Confirmed in Baker County Georgia|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912191627|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|bgcolor={{storm colour|cat2}} | EF2\n|W of [[Ocilla, Georgia|Ocilla]] to E of [[Ashton, Georgia|Ashton]]\n|[[Irwin County, Georgia|Irwin]], [[Ben Hill County, Georgia|Ben Hill]]\n|[[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n|{{Coord|31.5926|-83.399|name=Ocilla (Dec. 17, EF2)}}\n|16:35\u201317:09\n|{{convert|19.2|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|{{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}\n|Hundreds of trees were snapped by this high-end EF2 tornado, and several homes were severely damaged and sustained roof loss. The most severe damage occurred at Donelson Christian Academy in [[Mystic, Georgia|Mystic]], where multiple brick buildings had roofs torn off and sustained collapse of exterior walls. Barns and outbuildings were heavily damaged or destroyed, irrigation machinery was damaged, and a couple RVs were rolled over and heavily damaged.\n|<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Tallahassee, Florida|title=EF-2 Tornado Confirmed in Irwin County Georgia|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSTAE&e=201912191602|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 19, 2019|accessdate=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable tornadoes==\n===DeRidder \u2013 Rosepine \u2013 Alexandria \u2013 Pineville, Lousiana===\n[[File:AlexandriaLouisianaEF3tornado2019.jpg|thumb|left|EF3 damage to the Hope Baptist School in Alexandria, Louisiana.]]\nDuring the afternoon of December 16, a strong, long-tracked and damaging tornado touched down in [[DeRidder, Louisiana]]. The tornado was initially weak, causing minor EF0 to EF1 tree and roof damage in DeRidder. The tornado exited DeRidder, widening and strengthening as it continued northeastward into [[Vernon Parish, Louisiana|Vernon Parish]] and reaching EF3 strength as it passed to the southeast of [[Rosepine, Louisiana|Rosepine]]. Severe damage occurred along Mac Sterling Road, John Brewer Road, and Borel Road, where a couple of manufactured homes were obliterated with the debris scattered long distances through nearby fields. Outbuildings were destroyed, many large trees were snapped or uprooted, and some frame homes sustained partial to total roof loss. A few of these frame homes sustained some collapse of exterior walls as well. A 59-year old woman was killed in her home by the tornado in this area. The tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as it continued to the northeast, crossing [[Louisiana Highway 10]], where a church lost a portion of its metal roof and outbuildings were destroyed. Numerous trees were snapped as well. EF2 damage occurred beyond this point as the tornado moved through forested areas of [[Fort Polk]], snapping and uprooting countless trees. A structure sustained loss of its metal roof and collapse of brick facade in this area as well.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> Exiting Fort Polk, the tornado narrowed and weakened again, causing EF0 to EF1 tree damage is it moved through unpopulated areas. Additional minor EF0 and EF1 tree damage occurred as the tornado continued into [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]], moving to the northeast as it passed near [[Hineston, Louisiana|Hineston]] and [[Otis, Louisiana|Otis]]. Restrengthening then occurred as extensive EF2 tree damage occurred near the Kincaid Reservoir. Numerous trees were snapped and denuded, and a few sustained some low-end debarking. Maintaining EF2 strength, the strong tornado then entered the west side of [[Alexandria, Louisiana|Alexandria]]. Numerous mobile homes were thrown and destroyed at a mobile home sales business along Ross Lane, while nearby homes sustained significant roof damage. A few outbuildings were destroyed as well. The tornado strengthened and widened further just past this location, producing EF3 damage along Stovall Road. Several large metal buildings were completely destroyed in this area, and a large portion of the nearby Hope Baptist School was destroyed at EF3 intensity as well, with large amounts of debris was scattered throughout the area. The tornado then crossed [[Louisiana Highway 28]] and heavily damaged a sports complex along the north side of the highway. Continuing to the east-northeast, additional EF3 damage occurred as a convenience store was destroyed, and a nearby large metal-framed warehouse building was destroyed as well along John Allison Drive.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> A manufactured home was overturned in this area as well. In a nearby residential area, the tornado weakened to EF2 strength as large trees were downed, and homes had large portions of their roofs torn off. Continuing to the northeast through Alexandria, the tornado narrowed and weakened to EF1 strength, damaging trees and power poles as it crossed Bayou Rapides Road. Along Enterprise Road, a warehouse building sustained EF1 damage to its roof and doors. The tornado proceeded to cross the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] and entered [[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]], first causing EF1 damage to structures at the Pineville Municipal Airport. The tornado moved along a northeasterly path through residential areas of Pineville, snapping and uprooting numerous large trees. Some of these trees fell onto houses and caused heavy damage. A majority of the damage in Pineville was rated EF1, though a small pocket of EF2 damage occurred along Edgewood Drive, where a house sustained considerable structural damage. Past this area, the tornado continued to narrow and weaken, eventually dissipating after producing some EF0 tree limb damage along Donahue Ferry Road in Pineville.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nOverall, this EF3 tornado caused one fatality along its 62-mile long path. It had a peak width of {{convert|400|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>{{cite report|agency=National Weather Service Weather Forecast Office in Lake Charles, Louisiana|title=NWS Damage Survey for 12/16/19 Tornado Event|url=https://mesonet.agron.iastate.edu/wx/afos/p.php?pil=PNSLCH&e=201912182057|publisher=Iowa Environmental Mesonet|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n===Laurel \u2013 Sandersville \u2013 Shubuta \u2013 Mannassa, Mississippi/Lisman, Alabama===\n[[File:LaurelMississippiEF3tornado2019.jpg|thumb|left|EF3 damage to the Wade Services manufacturing plant near Laurel, Mississippi.]]\nThis strong, long-tracked tornado touched down during the late evening hours of December 16, at Hesler Noble Field in southwestern [[Laurel, Mississippi]]. Past the airport, the tornado caused EF0 to EF1 damage at the Dixie Golf Club, where trees and tree limbs were snapped and fencing was blown over. The tornado moved along a northeastward path through the southwest side of Laurel, downing trees and causing minor roof damage to homes. Metal roofing was torn off of a three-story motel along Jefferson street as well. Damage along this section of the path was rated EF0 to EF1 in intensity. Crossing South 16th Avenue, the tornado reached EF2 strength, where a small brick office building sustained roof and exterior wall loss, and a strip mall was heavily damaged. The roof of a hotel was lifted up and dropped back down onto the building, and a semi-truck and flatbed trailer carrying automobiles was flipped over and dragged. Continuing to the northeast through Laurel, the tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as numerous homes, warehouses, apartment buildings, and other structures sustained minor to moderate roof damage. One large building lost roughly 20% of its metal roof, and sustained collapse of brick facade. A [[Piggly Wiggly]] grocery store also sustained minor EF0 roof and exterior damage in this area as well, and numerous trees and a few power poles were downed. The tornado continued to the northeast through residential neighborhoods at EF1 intensity, snapping and uprooting trees and causing roof damage to additional homes. Some trees fell onto houses and cars as well. A metal self-storage building was partially destroyed along North 1st Avenue, and a large warehouse building near North Railroad Avenue sustained considerable roof damage. The tornado reached EF2 intensity again as moved through the eastern part of Laurel, where a house had its roof torn off and other homes sustained lesser roof damage. The Nora Davis Magnet school also lost much of its roof in this area. The tornado then reached EF3 intensity as it exited Laurel and crossed [[Interstate 59]], snapping and uprooting numerous trees, and toppling several large metal truss transmission towers to the ground. EF3 damage continued as the tornado then completely destroyed the Wade Services manufacturing plant, along with several other metal buildings and an office building on the property. Northeast of this area, the tornado momentarily weakened and caused EF1 tree damage as it moved along the east side of Interstate 59. The tornado became strong again as it then impacted the southern fringes of [[Sandersville, Mississippi|Sandersville]] at EF2 strength, where a house sustained loss of much of its roof, along with some second floor exterior walls. Another home sustained major roof damage, outbuildings were damaged or destroyed, numerous large trees were snapped or uprooted, and two people sustained minor injuries in the Sandersville area.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref> Past Sandersville, the tornado weakened back to EF1 strength as it struck the Mississippi Choctaw Reservation, where homes sustained roof and garage damage, a small pavilion collapsed, trees were downed, and headstones were tipped over at a cemetery. EF0 and EF1 damage to trees and homes continued through the extreme northwestern corner of [[Wayne County, Mississippi|Wayne County]] and into the southwestern corner of [[Clarke County, Mississippi|Clarke County]], though a small pocket of EF2 damage occurred along County Road 223, where numerous large trees were snapped and a mobile home was rolled and destroyed. Additional EF2 damage occurred as the tornado crossed [[U.S. Route 45]] north of [[Shubuta, Mississippi|Shubuta]], where a well-built home had most if its roof torn off. Northeast of Shubuta, numerous trees were snapped and uprooted at EF1 strength as the tornado moved through rural areas. A few outbuildings and mobile homes were damaged as well. A final area of EF2 damage occurred to the southwest of the small community of [[Mannassa, Mississippi|Mannassa]], where a well-built home along County Road 664 sustained destruction of its attached garage, and had a large portion of its roof torn off. A nearby mobile home was rolled and destroyed as well. Northeast of Mannassa, the tornado weakened to EF0 strength as it approached the Alabama border, causing only tree limb damage in rural areas. The tornado then regained EF1 strength as it crossed into [[Choctaw County, Alabama]], downing trees and destroying a mobile home. Additional trees were snapped or uprooted, and a house sustained partial removal of its roof before the tornado dissipated to the west-northwest of [[Lisman, Alabama]] after traveling {{convert|61.31|mi|km|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\nThe tornado was rated EF3 and injured two people. It reached a peak width of {{convert|350|yd|m|abbr=on|sortable=on}}.<ref>https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/stormevents/eventdetails.jsp?id=865251</ref><ref>https://apps.dat.noaa.gov/stormdamage/damageviewer/</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019 tornado outbreaks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tornado outbreak of December 16-17, 2019}}\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Alabama]]\n[[Category:2019 in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:2019 in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:2019 in Mississippi]]\n[[Category:December 2019 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2019 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:Tornadoes of 2019]]\n[[Category:F3 tornadoes]]\n", "name_user": "PohranicniStraze", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tornado_outbreak_of_December_16%E2%80%9317,_2019"}
{"title_page": "Zechariah (New Testament figure)", "text_new": "Zechariah \n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n<!-- leave in; navigate here via the Prophets of Islam template, and it may be helpful to have a disam route to reach Zechariah (Hebrew prophet) -->\n{{Infobox saint\n|name           = Zechariah\n|birth_date     = 1st century BC\n|death_date     = 1st century BC (or early AD)\n|birth_place    = [[Hebron]] (Joshua 21:11), the [[Levant]]\n|death_place    = [[Jerusalem]] (Matthew 23:35), the Levant\n|venerated_in   = [[Catholic Church]]<br>[[Orthodox Church]]<Br>[[Oriental Orthodox Church]]<br>[[Anglicanism]]<br>[[Lutheranism]]<br>[[Islam]]\n|image          = Cappella tornabuoni, 10, annuncio dell'angelo a zaccaria.jpg\n|imagesize      = 250px\n|caption        = ''[[Tornabuoni Chapel#Apparition of the Angel to Zechariah|Annunciation of the Angel to Zechariah]]'' by [[Domenico Ghirlandaio]] (1490, [[fresco]] in the [[Tornabuoni Chapel]], [[Florence]])\n|titles         = Priest, Prophet<!-- prophet in Bible also -->, Guardian of Mary, Devotee<!-- These last two are titles accorded in the Qur'an -->, Martyr<ref>[https://detroitcatholic.com/news/gary-michuta/did-john-the-baptist-s-father-die-a-martyr Did John the Baptist\u2019s father die a martyr?]</ref>\n|canonized_date = Pre-Congregation \n|feast_day      = September 5 \u2013 Eastern Orthodox<br>September 5 \u2013 Lutheran<br>September 23 \u2013 Roman Catholic\n}}\n\n==Biblical account==\n[[File:Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem. Georgian frescoes 01.JPG|thumb|Zechariah and St. John the Baptist. A medieval Georgian fresco from [[Monastery of the Cross]], [[Jerusalem]].]]\n\nAccording to the [[Gospel of Luke]], during the reign of king [[Herod the Great|Herod]], there was a priest named Zechariah, of the course of [[Abijah|Abia]], whose wife [[Elizabeth (Biblical person)|Elizabeth]] was also of the priestly family of [[Aaron]]. The [[Four Evangelists|evangelist]] states that both the parents were righteous before God, since they were \"blameless\" in observing the commandments and ordinances of the Lord. When the events related in Luke began, their marriage was still childless, because Elizabeth was \"barren\", and they were both \"well advanced in years\" ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:5-7|9|Luke 1:5&ndash;7}}).\n\nThe duties at the [[temple in Jerusalem]] alternated between each of the family lines that had descended from those appointed by king [[David]] ({{bibleverse|1Chronicles|24:1-19|9|1st Chronicles 24:1&ndash;19}}).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120720085450/http://www.avbtab.org/rc/read/dedicate.htm THE Dedication (Jesus' birth)] \"The priests serve 4 weeks per year: 1 week twice a year in courses, and the two week-long feasts, unleavened bread and tabernacles. Pentecost is a one-day observance, which would have come before Zacharias' (the 8th) course began, or at the latest, the 1st day of his course, which was from 12 thru 18 Sivan, or noon on the 19th, if Josephus is correct that courses changed at noon on the sabbaths.\" Josephus Antiquities b.7 ch.14 s.7 \"eight days, from sabbath to sabbath.\" Josephus against Apion b.2 sect.8 \"mid-day\".</ref> Luke states that during the week when it was the duty of Zechariah's family line to serve at \"the temple of the Lord\", the lot for performing the incense offering had fallen to Zechariah ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:8-11|9|Luke 1:8&ndash;11}}\n\n\n==In Islam==\n[[File:Aleppo - Prophet Zakariyya.JPG|thumb|right|260px|The tomb of Zechariah within the [[Great Mosque of Aleppo]], Syria]]\n{{Islamic prophets|Prophets in the Quran}}\nZechariah ([[Arabic]]: \u0632\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0627 Zakariyy\u0101) is also a [[prophets and messengers in Islam|prophet in Islam]], and is mentioned in the [[Qur'an]] as the father of John the Baptist. Zechariah is also believed by some Muslims to have been a [[martyr]]. An old tradition narrates that Zakariyah was sawed in half,<ref>''A-Z of Prophets in Islam and Judaism'', B. M. Wheeler, ''Zechariah, Father of John''</ref> in a death which resembles that attributed to [[Isaiah]] in ''[[Lives of the Prophets]]''.\n\nZakariyah was a righteous priest<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Lives of the Prophets'', Leila Azzam, ''Zacharias and John''</ref> and prophet of God whose office was in the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]]. He would frequently be in charge of managing the services of the temple<ref>Abdullah Yusuf Ali, Qur'anic commentary to Chapter 19</ref> and he would always remain steadfast in prayer to God.\n\n\nMuslim [[theology]] maintains that Zakariyah , along with [[John the Baptist]] and Jesus, ushered in a new era of prophets \u2013 all of whom came from the priestly descent of [[Amram]], the father of the prophet [[Aaron]]. The fact that, of all the priests, it was Zakariyah who was given the duty of keeping care of Mary shows his status as a pious man. Zakariyah  is frequently praised in the Qur'an as a prophet of God and righteous man. One such appraisal is in sura [[al-An'am]]: \"And Zakariyah and Yahya and Isa and Eliyas. Each one was of the righteous.\"{{Cite quran|6|85|t=p}}\n\nQur'an translator [[Abdullah Yusuf Ali]] offers commentary on this one line<ref name=\"YusufAliN905\"/> \u2013 suggesting that these particular prophets make a spiritual connection with one another. He points out that Yahya was a relative of Isa, while [[Elijah|Eliyas]]  was one who was present at the [[Transfiguration of Jesus|Transfiguration of Isa]] <ref>{{bibleref|Matthew|17:3|9}}: \"And, behold, there appeared unto them Moses and Elias talking with him.\"</ref> on the [[Mount of Transfiguration|Mount]], as mentioned in the New Testament. Zakariyah  meanwhile, through marriage, was the uncle of Isa and his son Yayha was referred to as Eliyas in the New Testament.<ref>{{bibleref2|Matthew|11:14-15|9|Matthew 11:14&ndash;15}}: \"And if ye will receive it, this is Elias, which was for to come. [15] He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biblical narratives and the Quran|Biblical narratives and the Qur'an]]\n*''[[Qisas Al-Anbiya|Qi\u1e63a\u1e63 al-'Anbiy\u0101\u2019]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u0650\u0640\u0635\u064e\u0640\u0635 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0646\u0640\u06e2\u0628\u0650\u0640\u064a\u064e\u0640\u0627\u0621}}, Stories of the Prophets (in Islam))\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{EBD|Zacharias}}\n{{Commons category|Saint Zachary}}{{Clear}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ocafs.oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=102502 Prophet Zachariah the father of St John the Baptist] Orthodox [[icon]] and [[synaxarion]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Gospel harmony|Life of Jesus]]: [[Virgin birth of Jesus|Conception of Jesus]]|||}}\n{{s-bef|before=Renovating the [[Second Temple]]<br>into [[Herod's Temple]] begins}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New Testament]]<br>Events}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Annunciation|Gabriel announces to Mary<br>that she will give birth to Jesus]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Testament people|prophets}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Prophets in the Qur'an}}\n{{Qur'anic people}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century BCE Jews]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC clergy]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Biblical people in Islam]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Luke]]\n[[Category:Jewish priests]]\n[[Category:People in the canonical gospels]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Jews]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Massacre of the Innocents]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Christian saints]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Zechariah (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n<!-- leave in; navigate here via the Prophets of Islam template, and it may be helpful to have a disam route to reach Zechariah (Hebrew prophet) -->\n{{Infobox saint\n|name           = Zechariah\n|birth_date     = 1st century BC\n|death_date     = 1st century BC (or early AD)\n|birth_place    = [[Hebron]] (Joshua 21:11), the [[Levant]]\n|death_place    = [[Jerusalem]] (Matthew 23:35), the Levant\n|venerated_in   = [[Catholic Church]]<br>[[Orthodox Church]]<Br>[[Oriental Orthodox Church]]<br>[[Anglicanism]]<br>[[Lutheranism]]<br>[[Islam]]\n|image          = Cappella tornabuoni, 10, annuncio dell'angelo a zaccaria.jpg\n|imagesize      = 250px\n|caption        = ''[[Tornabuoni Chapel#Apparition of the Angel to Zechariah|Annunciation of the Angel to Zechariah]]'' by [[Domenico Ghirlandaio]] (1490, [[fresco]] in the [[Tornabuoni Chapel]], [[Florence]])\n|titles         = Priest, Prophet<!-- prophet in Bible also -->, Guardian of Mary, Devotee<!-- These last two are titles accorded in the Qur'an -->, Martyr<ref>[https://detroitcatholic.com/news/gary-michuta/did-john-the-baptist-s-father-die-a-martyr Did John the Baptist\u2019s father die a martyr?]</ref>\n|canonized_date = Pre-Congregation \n|feast_day      = September 5 \u2013 Eastern Orthodox<br>September 5 \u2013 Lutheran<br>September 23 \u2013 Roman Catholic\n}}\n\n'''Zechariah''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d6\u05db\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4}} ''Z\u0259\u1e35ary\u0101h'', \"remember [[Jah|Yah]]\"; {{lang-el|\u0396\u03b1\u03c7\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}}; '''Zacharias''' in [[Authorized King James Version|KJV]]; '''Zachary''' in the [[Douay-Rheims Bible]]; '''Zakariyy\u0101\u02be''' ({{lang-ar|\u0632\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0640\u0631\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0640\u0627}}) in [[Islamic tradition]]) is a figure in the [[New Testament]] [[Bible]] and the [[Quran]],<ref name=\"Cite quran|19|2|e=15|s=ns\">{{cite quran|19|2|e=15|s=ns}}</ref> hence venerated in [[Christianity]] and [[Islam]].<ref name=\"YusufAliN905\">Abdullah Yusuf Ali, ''[[The Holy Qur'an: Text, Translation and Commentary]]'', Note. '''905''': \"The third group consists not of men of action, but Preachers of Truth, who led solitary lives. Their epithet is: \"the Righteous.\" They form a connected group round Jesus. Zachariah was the father of John the Baptist, who is referenced as \"Elias, which was for to come\" (Matt 11:14); and John the Baptist is said to have been present and talked to Jesus at the Transfiguration on the Mount (Matt. 17:3).\"</ref> In the Bible, he is the father of [[John the Baptist]], a priest of the sons of [[Aaron]] in the [[Gospel of Luke]] (1:67-79), and the husband of [[Elizabeth (Biblical person)|Elizabeth]] who is a relative of the [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Virgin Mary]] (Luke, 1:36).<ref name=\"Cite luke|1:5\u201379\">[[Gospel of Luke]], {{bibleref2|Luke|1:5-79|KJV|1:5&ndash;79}}</ref>\n\n==Biblical account==\n[[File:Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem. Georgian frescoes 01.JPG|thumb|Zechariah and St. John the Baptist. A medieval Georgian fresco from [[Monastery of the Cross]], [[Jerusalem]].]]\n\nAccording to the [[Gospel of Luke]], during the reign of king [[Herod the Great|Herod]], there was a priest named Zechariah, of the course of [[Abijah|Abia]], whose wife [[Elizabeth (Biblical person)|Elizabeth]] was also of the priestly family of [[Aaron]]. The [[Four Evangelists|evangelist]] states that both the parents were righteous before God, since they were \"blameless\" in observing the commandments and ordinances of the Lord. When the events related in Luke began, their marriage was still childless, because Elizabeth was \"barren\", and they were both \"well advanced in years\" ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:5-7|9|Luke 1:5&ndash;7}}).\n\nThe duties at the [[temple in Jerusalem]] alternated between each of the family lines that had descended from those appointed by king [[David]] ({{bibleverse|1Chronicles|24:1-19|9|1st Chronicles 24:1&ndash;19}}).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120720085450/http://www.avbtab.org/rc/read/dedicate.htm THE Dedication (Jesus' birth)] \"The priests serve 4 weeks per year: 1 week twice a year in courses, and the two week-long feasts, unleavened bread and tabernacles. Pentecost is a one-day observance, which would have come before Zacharias' (the 8th) course began, or at the latest, the 1st day of his course, which was from 12 thru 18 Sivan, or noon on the 19th, if Josephus is correct that courses changed at noon on the sabbaths.\" Josephus Antiquities b.7 ch.14 s.7 \"eight days, from sabbath to sabbath.\" Josephus against Apion b.2 sect.8 \"mid-day\".</ref> Luke states that during the week when it was the duty of Zechariah's family line to serve at \"the temple of the Lord\", the lot for performing the incense offering had fallen to Zechariah ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:8-11|9|Luke 1:8&ndash;11}}).\n\nThe Gospel of Luke states that while Zechariah ministered at the [[Altar (Bible)#Altar of Incense|altar of incense]], an angel of the Lord appeared and announced to him that his wife would give birth to a son, whom he was to name John, and that this son would be the forerunner of the Lord ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:12-17|9|Luke 1:12&ndash;17}}). Citing their advanced age, Zechariah asked with disbelief for a sign whereby he would know the truth of this prophecy. In reply, the angel identified himself as [[Gabriel]], sent especially by God to make this announcement, and added that because of Zechariah's doubt he would be struck dumb and \"not able to speak, until the day that these things shall be performed\". Consequently, when he went out to the waiting worshippers in the temple's outer courts, he was unable to speak the customary blessing ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:18-22|9|Luke 1:18&ndash;22}}).\n\nAfter returning to his house in \"Hebron, in the hill ''country'' of Judah\",<ref>compare {{bibleverse|Luke|1:39-40|9|Luke 1:39&ndash;40}} with {{bibleverse|Joshua|21:11|KJV}} The [http://tsk.scripturetext.com/luke/1.htm ''Treasury of Scripture Knowledge''] says, \"This was most probably Hebron, a city of the priests, and situated in the hill country of Judea, ({{bibleverse|Joshua|11:21|KJV}}; {{bibleverse-nb|Joshua|21:11, 13|KJV}}) about 25 miles south of Jerusalem, and nearly 100 from Nazareth.\"</ref> his wife Elizabeth conceived. After Elizabeth completed her fifth month of pregnancy, her relative [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]] was visited by the same angel, Gabriel, overshadowed by the Holy Ghost and \u2013 though still a virgin \u2013 became pregnant with Jesus. Mary then travelled to visit her relative Elizabeth, having been told by the angel that Elizabeth was in her sixth month of pregnancy. Mary remained about three months before she returned to her own house ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:23-45|KJV}};{{bibleverse|Luke|1:56|KJV|56}}).\n\nElizabeth gave birth, and on the eighth day, when their son was to be [[circumcision|circumcised]] according to the commandment, her neighbours and relatives assumed that he was to be named after his father. Elizabeth, however, insisted that his name was to be John; so the family then questioned her husband. As soon as Zechariah had written on a writing table: \"His name is John\", he regained the power of speech, and blessed \"the Lord God of Israel\" with a [[prophecy]] known as the [[Benedictus (Song of Zechariah)|''Benedictus'']] or \"Song of Zechariah\" ({{bibleref|Luke|1:57\u201379|9}}). The child grew up and \"waxed strong in spirit\", but remained in the deserts of Jud\u00e6a until he assumed the ministry that was to earn him the name \"[[John the Baptist]]\"  ({{bibleverse|Luke|1:80|KJV}}; {{bibleverse-nb|Luke|3:2-3|KJV}}; [[Matthew 3:1]]).\n\n==Other Christian traditions==\n[[File:Tomb of Avshalom in the Kidron Valley;.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The so-called \"[[Tomb of Absalom]]\" or \"Absalom's Pillar\" in the [[Kidron Valley]], built in the 1st century CE; an inscription added three centuries later claims that it is Zechariah's tomb]]\n[[File:Cappella Tornabuoni, Zacharias Writes Down the Name of his Son 01.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Domenico Ghirlandaio]]'s fresco ''Zechariah Writes Down the Name of His Son'' (1490, [[fresco]] in the [[Tornabuoni Chapel]], [[Florence]])]]\n\n[[Origen]] suggested that the Zechariah mentioned in {{bibleref|Matthew|23:35|9}} as having been killed between the temple and the altar may be the father of John the Baptist.<ref>[[Reimund Bieringer]], ''The Corinthian Correspondence'' (Peeters Publishers, 1996), page 497, footnote 20, {{ISBN|978-9068317749}}.</ref> Orthodox [[Gospel of James|Christian tradition]] recounts that, at the time of the [[massacre of the Innocents]], when King [[Herod the Great|Herod]] ordered the slaughter of all males under the age of two in an attempt to prevent the prophesied Messiah from coming to Israel, Zechariah refused to divulge the whereabouts of his son (who was in hiding), and he was therefore murdered by Herod's soldiers. This is also recorded in the [[Infancy Gospel of James]], an [[New Testament apocrypha|apocryphal]] work from the 2nd century.\n\nThe Roman Catholic Church commemorates him as a [[saint]], along with Elizabeth, on September 23.<ref>''Martyrologium Romanum'' (Libreria Editrice Vaticana 2001 {{ISBN|88-209-7210-7}})</ref> He is also venerated as a prophet in the [[Calendar of Saints (Lutheran)|Calendar of Saints]] of the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod|Lutheran Church]] on September 5. The [[Eastern Orthodox Church]] also celebrates the [[feast day]] of Zechariah [[September 5 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)|on September 5]], together with [[Elizabeth (Biblical person)|Elizabeth]], who is considered a matriarch. Zechariah and Elizabeth are invoked in several prayers during the Orthodox [[Sacred Mysteries|Mystery]] [[Christian views of marriage#View of the Eastern Orthodox Church|of Crowning]] (Sacrament of Marriage), as the priest blesses the newly married couple, saying \"Thou who didst... accept Zechariah and Elizabeth, and didst make their offspring the [[John the Baptist|Forerunner]]...\" and \"...bless them, O Lord our God, as Thou didst Zechariah and Elizabeth...\". In the [[Greek Orthodox]] calendar, Zechariah and Elizabeth are also commemorated on June 24.\n\n[[Armenians]] believe that the [[Gandzasar Monastery]] in [[Nagorno Karabakh]], Azerbaijan contains relics of Zechariah. However, his relics were also kept in the Great Church of [[Constantinople]], where they were brought by the ''[[praefectus urbi]]'' [[Ursus (praefectus urbi)|Ursus]] on September 4, 415.<ref>''[[Chronicon Paschale]]'', ''sub anno'' 415.</ref>\n\nIn 2003, a 4th-century inscription on the so-called [[Tomb of Absalom]], a 1st-century monument in Jerusalem, was deciphered as, \"This is the tomb of Zachariah, the martyr, the holy priest, the father of John.\" This suggests to some scholars that it is the burial place of Zechariah the father of John the Baptist. Professor Gideon Foerster at the [[Hebrew University]] states that the inscription tallies with a 6th-century Christian text stating that Zechariah was buried with Simon the Elder and [[James the brother of Jesus]], and believes that both are authentic.<ref name=Haaretz>[http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=320531 Jewish Yad Avshalom revealed as a Christian shrine from Byzantine era], ''[[Haaretz]]'', July 22, 2003</ref> What makes the theory less plausible is the fact that the tomb is three centuries older than the Byzantine inscriptions, that a tomb with just two burial benches is unlikely to be used for three burials, as well as the fact that the identification of the tomb has repeatedly changed during its history.<ref name=\"ZiasPuech\">{{cite web|url= http://tfba.co/content/index.php/projects/34-tomb-of-absalom/46-the-tomb-of-absalom-reconsidered |author=[[Joe Zias]] and [[\u00c9mile Puech]] |year=2004 |title=The Tomb of Absalom Reconsidered |work= |publisher=The Foundation for Biblical Archaeology |accessdate=4 January 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==In Islam==\n[[File:Aleppo - Prophet Zakariyya.JPG|thumb|right|260px|The tomb of Zechariah within the [[Great Mosque of Aleppo]], Syria]]\n{{Islamic prophets|Prophets in the Quran}}\nZechariah ([[Arabic]]: \u0632\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0631\u0650\u064a\u064e\u0651\u0627 Zakariyy\u0101) is also a [[prophets and messengers in Islam|prophet in Islam]], and is mentioned in the [[Qur'an]] as the father of John the Baptist. Zechariah is also believed by some Muslims to have been a [[martyr]]. An old tradition narrates that Zakariyah was sawed in half,<ref>''A-Z of Prophets in Islam and Judaism'', B. M. Wheeler, ''Zechariah, Father of John''</ref> in a death which resembles that attributed to [[Isaiah]] in ''[[Lives of the Prophets]]''.\n\nZakariyah was a righteous priest<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">''Lives of the Prophets'', Leila Azzam, ''Zacharias and John''</ref> and prophet of God whose office was in the [[Second Temple]] in [[Jerusalem]]. He would frequently be in charge of managing the services of the temple<ref>Abdullah Yusuf Ali, Qur'anic commentary to Chapter 19</ref> and he would always remain steadfast in prayer to God.\n\nAs he reached his old age, Zakariyah began to worry over who would continue the legacy of preaching the message of God after his death and who would carry on the daily services of the temple after him. Zakariyah started to pray to God for a son. The praying for the birth of an offspring was not merely out of the desire for a child.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> He prayed both for himself and for the public \u2013 they needed a messenger, a man of God who would work in the service of the Lord after Zakariyah. Zakariyah had character and virtue and he wanted to transfer this to his spiritual heir as his most precious possession. His dream was to restore the household to the posterity of the [[Patriarchs (Bible)|Patriarch]] [[Jacob]], and to make sure the message of God was renewed for Israel. As the Qur'an recounts:\n{{Quote|A mention of the mercy of your Lord to His servant Zakariya. When he cried unto his Lord a cry in secret, saying: My Lord! Lo! the bones of me wax feeble and my head is shining with grey hair, and I have never been unblest in prayer to Thee, my Lord. Lo! I fear my kinsfolk after me, since my wife is barren. Oh, give me from Thy presence a successor who shall inherit of me and inherit (also) of the house of Jacob. And make him, my Lord, acceptable (unto Thee). {{cite quran|19|4|e=6|t=p}}}}\nAs a gift from God, Zakariyah  was given a son named ''Ya\u1e25y\u00e1'' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u062d\u064a\u0649}}, identified with [[John the Baptist]]), a name specially chosen for this child alone. Muslim tradition narrates that Zakariyah was ninety-two years old<ref>''Historical Dictionary of Prophets In Islam and Judaism'', B. M. Wheeler, ''Zechariah, father of John''</ref> when he was told of John's birth.\n\nIn accordance with Zakariyah\u2019s  prayer, God made John renew the message of God, which had been corrupted and lost by the Israelites.<ref>{{bibleref|Luke|1:16|9}}: \"And many of the children of Israel shall he turn to the Lord their God.\"</ref> As the Qur'an says:\n{{Quote|O Zachariah! Lo! We bring thee tidings of a son whose name is John; we have given the same name to none before (him). He said: My Lord! How can I have a son when my wife is barren and I have reached infirm old age? He said: So shall it be, your Lord says: It is easy to Me, and indeed I created you before, when you were nothing. He said: My Lord! give me a sign. He said: Your sign is that you will not be able to speak to the people three nights while in sound health.|{{cite quran|19|7|e=10|t=p}}}}\nAccording to the Qur'an, Zakariyah was the guardian of [[Mary in Islam|Maryam]] . The Qur'an states:\n{{Quote|(Remember) when the wife of [[Joachim#In Islam |'Imran]] said: My Lord! I have vowed unto Thee that which is in my belly as a consecrated (offering). Accept it from me. Lo! Thou, only Thou, art the Hearer, the Knower! And when she was delivered she said: My Lord! Lo! I am delivered of a female - Allah knew best of what she was delivered - the male is not as the female; and lo! I have named her Mary, and lo! I crave Thy protection for her and for her offspring from Satan the outcast. And her Lord accepted her with full acceptance and vouchsafed to her a goodly growth; and made Zachariah her guardian. Whenever Zachariah went into the sanctuary where she was, he found that she had food. He said: O Mary! Whence cometh unto thee this (food)? She answered: It is from Allah. Allah giveth without stint to whom He will.{{Cite quran|3|35|e=37|t=p}}}}\n\nMuslim [[theology]] maintains that Zakariyah , along with [[John the Baptist]] and Jesus, ushered in a new era of prophets \u2013 all of whom came from the priestly descent of [[Amram]], the father of the prophet [[Aaron]]. The fact that, of all the priests, it was Zakariyah who was given the duty of keeping care of Mary shows his status as a pious man. Zakariyah  is frequently praised in the Qur'an as a prophet of God and righteous man. One such appraisal is in sura [[al-An'am]]: \"And Zakariyah and Yahya and Isa and Eliyas. Each one was of the righteous.\"{{Cite quran|6|85|t=p}}\n\nQur'an translator [[Abdullah Yusuf Ali]] offers commentary on this one line<ref name=\"YusufAliN905\"/> \u2013 suggesting that these particular prophets make a spiritual connection with one another. He points out that Yahya was a relative of Isa, while [[Elijah|Eliyas]]  was one who was present at the [[Transfiguration of Jesus|Transfiguration of Isa]] <ref>{{bibleref|Matthew|17:3|9}}: \"And, behold, there appeared unto them Moses and Elias talking with him.\"</ref> on the [[Mount of Transfiguration|Mount]], as mentioned in the New Testament. Zakariyah  meanwhile, through marriage, was the uncle of Isa and his son Yayha was referred to as Eliyas in the New Testament.<ref>{{bibleref2|Matthew|11:14-15|9|Matthew 11:14&ndash;15}}: \"And if ye will receive it, this is Elias, which was for to come. [15] He that hath ears to hear, let him hear.\"</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Biblical narratives and the Quran|Biblical narratives and the Qur'an]]\n*''[[Qisas Al-Anbiya|Qi\u1e63a\u1e63 al-'Anbiy\u0101\u2019]]'' ({{lang-ar|\u0642\u0650\u0640\u0635\u064e\u0640\u0635 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0623\u064e\u0646\u0640\u06e2\u0628\u0650\u0640\u064a\u064e\u0640\u0627\u0621}}, Stories of the Prophets (in Islam))\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{EBD|Zacharias}}\n{{Commons category|Saint Zachary}}{{Clear}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://ocafs.oca.org/FeastSaintsViewer.asp?SID=4&ID=1&FSID=102502 Prophet Zachariah the father of St John the Baptist] Orthodox [[icon]] and [[synaxarion]]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Gospel harmony|Life of Jesus]]: [[Virgin birth of Jesus|Conception of Jesus]]|||}}\n{{s-bef|before=Renovating the [[Second Temple]]<br>into [[Herod's Temple]] begins}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[New Testament]]<br>Events}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Annunciation|Gabriel announces to Mary<br>that she will give birth to Jesus]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Testament people|prophets}}\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Prophets in the Qur'an}}\n{{Qur'anic people}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1st-century BCE Jews]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC clergy]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Biblical people in Islam]]\n[[Category:Gospel of Luke]]\n[[Category:Jewish priests]]\n[[Category:People in the canonical gospels]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Jews]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Massacre of the Innocents]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Christian saints]]\n", "name_user": "58.110.225.55", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(ture story)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zechariah_(New_Testament_figure)"}
{"title_page": "WinRed", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| image = Winred-logo.png\n| caption = \n| formation = 2019\n| type = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| affiliations = Republican Party\n| name = WinRed\n| size = \n| membership = \n| website = {{url| winred.com}}\n| location =\n}}\n'''WinRed''' is a [[conservative]] fundraising platform endorsed by the [[Republican National Committee]] and [[Donald Trump|President Donald Trump]]. It was launched to compete with [[ActBlue]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] fundraising platform. \n\n==Product details==\nWinRed is a fundraising platform built for the Republican party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Crabtree |first1=Susan |title=Backlash Ensues as RNC's WinRed Fundraising Hammer Falls |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2019/07/16/backlash_ensues_as_rncs_winred_fundraising_hammer_falls.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=RealClearPolitics |date=16 July 2019}}</ref> It was built to compete with the older Democrat platform [[ActBlue]]. The national Republican Party, the Trump re-election campaign, and other state- and local-level races across the United States used the platform as of late 2019.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Alex |title=WinRed, new GOP donor platform, reaps impeachment windfall, rakes in millions since probe launch |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/winred-impeachment-republican-donor-platform-windfall |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nWinRed merges Revv, a GOP payment processing firm founded by [[Gerrit AP NEWS (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]], and DataTrust, the party's voter data repository. The platform allows one-click donations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |title=GOP unveils fundraising tool to rival Democrats' ActBlue |url=https://apnews.com/f845d66c4dd94fb8ae2cd94a3c1aed40 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=AP News |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fox News]] notes that a contributing factor to Democratic success in the 2018 midterm elections was the party's ability to take in online small-dollar donations, in part through their platform [[ActBlue]]. WinRed was built to oppose this capacity.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> Republican party leadership began discussing the possibility of building a competitor to WinBlue within days of the 2018 midterm results. WinRed was called Patriot Pass in its initial announcements, with an expected release date of February 2019.<ref name=\"Politico-Jan2019-JuiceSmallDollar\"/><ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\"/> However, the name was changed following Robert Krafts's complaints that the name resembled that of his football team, the Patriots.<ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\">{{cite news |last1=Overby |first1=Peter |title=Red Shift: How Republicans Plan To Catch Democrats In Online Fundraising |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/736990455/red-shift-how-republicans-plan-to-catch-democrats-in-online-fundraising |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=1 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the RNC and the Trump administration applied heavy pressure to incentivize all Republican campaigns to use the platform.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\"/>\n\n==Revenue==\nIn the three months after launch, WinRed raised over $30 million, surpassing its goal of $20-25 million for the first quarter. [[Gerrit Lansing (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]] and [[Sam Miele (businessman)|Sam Miele]], the founders of WinRed, as well as well as various Republican operatives, attributed some of this success to the impeachment effort at the time. In the day after announcement of impeachment, the Trump campaign and the RNC received over $5 million dollars.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> In its first six months, WinRed took in $100 million.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\">{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1=Danny |last2=Thrush |first2=Glenn |title=How the Trump Campaign Took Over the G.O.P. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/us/trump-campaign-brad-parscale.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\nAs part of party negotiations to launch WinRed, the platform Victory Pass was expected to close. The platform Anedot was not involved in discussions among party leadership.<ref name=\"Politico-Jan2019-JuiceSmallDollar\">{{cite news |last1=Isenstadt |first1=Alex |title=Exclusive: GOP reaches landmark agreement to juice small-dollar fundraising |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/21/republican-fundraising-patriot-pass-1116642 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=POLITICO |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration sent a cease-and-desist letter to formal rival [[Anedot]]. Any Republican candidate or lawmaker who uses Anedot or Give.GOP will no longer receive any support from the Republican Party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n== Reception ==\nFollowing the aggressive push for Republican campaigns to use WinRed, many party officials, fundraisers, and campaign operatives criticized the effort on several grounds. Some critiqued the requirement that campaigns use WinRed, arguing that the effort went against Republican free-market principles while pushing aside older services preferred by campaigns, sure as Anedot or Give.GOP. Others expressed concern about profits, noting that it was unclear who stood to gain from use of the service and comparing the higher fees of WinRed to those of competitors.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| image = Winred-logo.png\n| caption = \n| formation = 2019\n| type = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| affiliations = Republican Party\n| name = WinRed\n| size = \n| membership = \n| website = {{url| winred.com}}\n| location =\n}}\n'''WinRed''' is a [[conservative]] fundraising platform endorsed by the [[Republican National Committee]] and [[Donald Trump]]. It was launched to compete with [[ActBlue]], the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] fundraising platform. \n\n==Product details==\nWinRed is a fundraising platform built for the Republican party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Crabtree |first1=Susan |title=Backlash Ensues as RNC's WinRed Fundraising Hammer Falls |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2019/07/16/backlash_ensues_as_rncs_winred_fundraising_hammer_falls.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=RealClearPolitics |date=16 July 2019}}</ref> It was built to compete with the older Democrat platform [[ActBlue]]. The national Republican Party, the Trump re-election campaign, and other state- and local-level races across the United States used the platform as of late 2019.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Pappas |first1=Alex |title=WinRed, new GOP donor platform, reaps impeachment windfall, rakes in millions since probe launch |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/winred-impeachment-republican-donor-platform-windfall |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=Fox News |date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nWinRed merges Revv, a GOP payment processing firm founded by [[Gerrit AP NEWS (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]], and DataTrust, the party's voter data repository. The platform allows one-click donations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |title=GOP unveils fundraising tool to rival Democrats' ActBlue |url=https://apnews.com/f845d66c4dd94fb8ae2cd94a3c1aed40 |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=AP News |date=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fox News]] notes that a contributing factor to Democratic success in the 2018 midterm elections was the party's ability to take in online small-dollar donations, in part through their platform [[ActBlue]]. WinRed was built to oppose this capacity.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> Republican party leadership began discussing the possibility of building a competitor to WinBlue within days of the 2018 midterm results. WinRed was called Patriot Pass in its initial announcements, with an expected release date of February 2019.<ref name=\"Politico-Jan2019-JuiceSmallDollar\"/><ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\"/> However, the name was changed following Robert Krafts's complaints that the name resembled that of his football team, the Patriots.<ref name=\"NPR-RedShift-July2019\">{{cite news |last1=Overby |first1=Peter |title=Red Shift: How Republicans Plan To Catch Democrats In Online Fundraising |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/07/01/736990455/red-shift-how-republicans-plan-to-catch-democrats-in-online-fundraising |accessdate=7 April 2020 |work=NPR |date=1 July 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the RNC and the Trump administration applied heavy pressure to incentivize all Republican campaigns to use the platform.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\"/>\n\n==Revenue==\nIn the three months after launch, WinRed raised over $30 million, surpassing its goal of $20-25 million for the first quarter. [[Gerrit Lansing (technologist)|Gerrit Lansing]], the founder of WinRed, as well as well as various Republican operatives, attributed some of this success to the impeachment effort at the time. In the day after announcement of impeachment, the Trump campaign and the RNC received over $5 million dollars.<ref name=\"Fox-impeachment-2019\" /> In its first six months, WinRed took in $100 million.<ref name=\"NYT-takeover-2020\">{{cite news |last1=Hakim |first1=Danny |last2=Thrush |first2=Glenn |title=How the Trump Campaign Took Over the G.O.P. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/us/trump-campaign-brad-parscale.html |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Competitors==\nAs part of party negotiations to launch WinRed, the platform Victory Pass was expected to close. The platform Anedot was not involved in discussions among party leadership.<ref name=\"Politico-Jan2019-JuiceSmallDollar\">{{cite news |last1=Isenstadt |first1=Alex |title=Exclusive: GOP reaches landmark agreement to juice small-dollar fundraising |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/21/republican-fundraising-patriot-pass-1116642 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=POLITICO |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Trump administration sent a cease-and-desist letter to formal rival [[Anedot]]. Any Republican candidate or lawmaker who uses Anedot or Give.GOP will no longer receive any support from the Republican Party.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n== Reception ==\nFollowing the aggressive push for Republican campaigns to use WinRed, many party officials, fundraisers, and campaign operatives criticized the effort on several grounds. Some critiqued the requirement that campaigns use WinRed, arguing that the effort went against Republican free-market principles while pushing aside older services preferred by campaigns, sure as Anedot or Give.GOP. Others expressed concern about profits, noting that it was unclear who stood to gain from use of the service and comparing the higher fees of WinRed to those of competitors.<ref name=\"Backlash-RCP-2019\" />\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Republican Party (United States)]]\n", "name_user": "Birmington354", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed Donald Trump to President Donald Trump.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WinRed"}
